
🔹 What is a Tag in Source Code?
A tag is a label assigned to a specific point (commit) in the code repository to mark important versions like releases.
Example: v1.0, v2.1

🔹 What is a Release?
A release is a packaged version of the software that is made available for users. It usually includes:
Stable code
Documentation
Release notes

Platforms like GitHub allow developers to create releases linked to tags.

🎯 Purpose of Tags

🔖 Version Identification
Helps identify specific versions of the code (e.g., v1.0, v2.0)

🧭 Easy Navigation
Developers can quickly go back to a specific version

🧪 Testing & Debugging
Helps track bugs in a particular version

📦 Supports Releases
Tags are used to create official releases

🎯 Purpose of Releases

🚀 Distribute Software
Provides users with a stable version of the application

📄 Documentation & Notes
Includes release notes explaining changes and updates

🔐 Version Control
Keeps track of different versions over time

📥 Downloadable Files
Users can download compiled files or source code

